Claude responded: #include <atomic> gives you access to atomic types from the C++ standard library — specifically the std::atomic<T> template.
#include <atomic> gives you access to atomic types from the C++ standard library — specifically the std::atomic<T> template.

The problem it solves:

In your Jeopardy game, two threads run at the same time — the main thread waiting for player input, and the timer thread counting down. Both threads read and write shared variables like timerExpired and answerReceived. Without protection, this causes a race condition: both threads could try to read/write the variable at the exact same moment, leading to unpredictable behavior or crashes.

What std::atomic does:

It guarantees that reads and writes to that variable are indivisible — no thread can see a half-updated value, and no two threads can modify it simultaneously. In your code:

cpp
std::atomic<bool> timerExpired(false);
std::atomic<bool> answerReceived(false);
These two booleans can safely be read and written from both threads at the same time. When the timer thread does:

cpp
timerExpired.store(true);


When the game starts, it asks how many players (3 or 4) and collects each player's name:
cppstd::vector<Player> players(numPlayers);
for (int i = 0; i < numPlayers; i++) {
    std::cout << "Enter name for Player " << (i + 1) << ": ";
    std::getline(std::cin, players[i].name);
}
Each Player is a simple struct holding a name and a score, stored in a std::vector.
During the game, players rotate turns using a single index variable:
cppint currentPlayer = 0;
// ...after each question:
currentPlayer = (currentPlayer + 1) % players.size();
The % (modulo) operator wraps the index back to 0 after the last player, so turns cycle endlessly: Player 1 → 2 → 3 → 1 → 2 → 3...